<!--
  REVIEWED TRANSLATIONS — Step 6.M-A.2-R (2026-06-06)
  Spanish (es) UI translations. Originally machine-drafted in Step
  6.M-A.2 (commit 66ba309) and then reviewed by native Spanish
  speaker (Diego).

  Project-owner adjustments to Diego's review:
   - mood_save_failed: restored multi-line "\nInténtalo de nuevo." to
     match the multi-line pattern of EN/RU/UK/RO and preserve the
     retry-hint UX. Diego's reviewed value covered only the first
     sentence.
   - home_greeting and home_greeting_with_mood: used gender-neutral
     "Hola otra vez" instead of Diego's "Bienvenido de nuevo". Diego
     himself flagged the gender issue in his Notes and suggested this
     alternative. A future post-MVP step will introduce profile-aware
     adaptive copy (gender, age tier).

  Style notes (Diego's decisions, accepted as-is):
   - Mood is rendered as "estado" everywhere, not "ánimo".
   - Companion is "Compañero Elyria", not "Acompañante Elyria".
   - Emotions use adjective form (Triste, Ansioso, Cansado, Solo,
     Abrumado, Tranquilo, Esperanzado, Agradecido, Orgulloso, En paz,
     Motivado, Enfadado). This differs from RU/UK/RO (which use
     nouns) but is the convention Diego recommends for Spanish
     wellbeing apps. Adjectives are in masculine form by default
     and will be addressed by the future profile-aware copy step.
   - Spain-leaning vocabulary in a few places: Enfadado (vs Enojado),
     Media (vs Promedio), Empezar (vs Comenzar), Finalizar práctica
     (vs Terminar práctica). Acceptable across both Spain and Latin
     America per Diego.
   - "check-in" and "mindfulness" kept as English loanwords (Spanish
     wellbeing-app convention).
   - Tone: informal T-form (tú), soft, non-imperative where possible.

  No DRAFT markers remain. This file is release-ready for Spanish.
-->
